00:35:38.395 --> 00:35:43.680
DAN GALPIN: So as we talk
about this past year, what

00:35:43.680 --> 00:35:45.830
have you seen in
terms of Asia and it

00:35:45.830 --> 00:35:47.050
being a force in your games?

00:35:47.050 --> 00:35:49.100
I know it's one of the
challenges for game makers

00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:50.600
that are outside
of Asia is actually

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:53.080
kind of cracking
into that market.

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:55.294
How has that worked
for your team?

00:35:55.294 --> 00:35:57.460
GUILHERME LACHAUT: So we're
really a global company.

00:35:57.460 --> 00:35:59.250
So we do have offices
all around the world.

00:35:59.250 --> 00:36:00.958
But it's true that
when you look at Asia,

00:36:00.958 --> 00:36:02.520
it's a really specific market.

00:36:02.520 --> 00:36:04.820
It has its own customs.

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:07.900
The users are really playing
different types of games.

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:11.640
So as a publisher, I think for
us it's really important-- what

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:13.820
we're trying to do is
really to adapt our offers.

00:36:13.820 --> 00:36:17.410
So content of our games,
pricing, and the way

00:36:17.410 --> 00:36:18.370
we're addressing them.

00:36:21.420 --> 00:36:23.580
We went from being
global to trying

00:36:23.580 --> 00:36:26.060
to offer the same service,
then localization,

00:36:26.060 --> 00:36:28.780
and now it's really offering
a customized experience

00:36:28.780 --> 00:36:31.290
to those kinds of markets.

00:36:31.290 --> 00:36:33.030
DAN GALPIN: Cool.

00:36:33.030 --> 00:36:33.980
KEITH PICHELMAN: Yeah.

00:36:33.980 --> 00:36:36.646
So Concrete Software, we've been
around for almost 11 years now,

00:36:36.646 --> 00:36:37.795
making mobile games.

00:36:37.795 --> 00:36:40.160
It's been quite a ride.

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:43.440
And the biggest change it
seemed like over the long haul

00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:44.450
has been pricing.

00:36:44.450 --> 00:36:47.370
We started off, we were selling
mobile games for $20 a shot.

00:36:47.370 --> 00:36:48.956
And we got press
down, kind of went

00:36:48.956 --> 00:36:50.960
to advertising a little bit.

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:53.660
But then, really,
this last year we

00:36:53.660 --> 00:36:56.439
had to make a fundamental
shift, where we really

00:36:56.439 --> 00:36:57.980
had to start thinking
about our games

00:36:57.980 --> 00:36:59.938
as not just being a
product to get out the door

00:36:59.938 --> 00:37:02.120
and trying to make a great
game, get a good review.

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:04.380
But our games are now services.

00:37:04.380 --> 00:37:08.430
We really think about, when make
a game, that this is a service.

00:37:08.430 --> 00:37:10.380
And that's where
Quests will come in.

00:37:10.380 --> 00:37:13.960
Or we can add a lot more
content for our users.

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:16.320
But yeah, this
last year-- we used

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:19.130
to release maybe six,
seven games a year.

00:37:19.130 --> 00:37:21.220
And now, this last
year, we released one.

00:37:21.220 --> 00:37:24.930
It's really been a
challenge to make sure

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:27.540
that we retain our users, that
we always have new content,

00:37:27.540 --> 00:37:30.400
and that we really think
more as a service company.

00:37:33.410 --> 00:37:38.510
LLOYD TULLUES: So for us, it's
really been a mindset change.

00:37:38.510 --> 00:37:41.290
If we're going to talk about
Asia just for a second,

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:44.980
in the past-- I've been in the
industry for 13 some odd years.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:48.910
And when we make
a product, you go

00:37:48.910 --> 00:37:50.210
through localization efforts.

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:52.626
You just translate everything
and you kick it out the door

00:37:52.626 --> 00:37:54.700
and you open the rest
of the world likes it.

00:37:54.700 --> 00:37:57.400
But the mindset change on
our end, specifically now,

00:37:57.400 --> 00:37:59.720
is it's not just
about localization.

00:37:59.720 --> 00:38:01.322
It's about culturalization.

00:38:01.322 --> 00:38:06.930
Taking a game and really
adapting for the Asian market

00:38:06.930 --> 00:38:09.646
in a way that resonates to them.

00:38:09.646 --> 00:38:11.270
And oftentimes, we
get a product that's

00:38:11.270 --> 00:38:15.590
very different from the one that
we have in the United States.

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:18.090
And so that's been a very,
very big change for us.

00:38:18.090 --> 00:38:21.670
And then we've also gone through
the same learnings in terms of,

00:38:21.670 --> 00:38:26.900
you just can't go to the old
way of doing things, which

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.940
was make a thing, ship
a thing, and then pray.

00:38:29.940 --> 00:38:31.900
You now make a thing,
you ship a thing,

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:33.540
and then you keep
on building it.

00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:35.680
As you learn what
your users like,

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:38.690
you get into the
behavioral play patterns.

00:38:38.690 --> 00:38:41.535
You see what content
they really enjoy,

00:38:41.535 --> 00:38:43.270
and you keep building on that.

00:38:43.270 --> 00:38:47.575
You just keep on making the game
better for many years on end.

00:38:47.575 --> 00:38:49.450
DAN GALPIN: So when you
guys think of a game,

00:38:49.450 --> 00:38:52.140
how many updates in the
future are you guys thinking,

00:38:52.140 --> 00:38:54.710
in terms of when you have a
game that you know is a service?

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:56.889
How far in the future
are you thinking?

00:38:56.889 --> 00:38:57.930
LLOYD TULLUES: Very long.

00:38:57.930 --> 00:39:06.400
We will plan for years on end
for it a successful title.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:10.140
SOURABH AHUJA: I'll quickly
comment on Asia, too.

00:39:10.140 --> 00:39:12.582
On the culturalization
part, it is the key.

00:39:12.582 --> 00:39:14.290
We've had one or two
successes, but we've

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:17.150
realized-- I personally
went there, too,

00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:21.080
and we partnered with companies
like [INAUDIBLE] in giving them

00:39:21.080 --> 00:39:24.860
our game engines and
letting use their expertise

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:29.420
for the Japanese audience to
adapt to the monetizations.

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:31.270
Like the live events,
those kind of things,

00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:32.410
which work really well.

00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:35.260
The characters, I think
that culturalization

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:38.951
is the key to success
in Asia right now.

00:39:38.951 --> 00:39:40.950
DAN GALPIN: When you talk
about culturalization,

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:45.130
are you talking about changes
to marketing, to game play,

00:39:45.130 --> 00:39:47.720
to just character design?

00:39:47.720 --> 00:39:49.220
How deep do you end up going?

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:52.000
SOURABH AHUJA: We're going
pretty deep for this project

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.320
with [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:56.430
They really liked
our 3-D engine we

00:39:56.430 --> 00:39:58.060
had for our game
"Heroes of Destiny."

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:01.236
And we like what they
are doing, of course.

00:40:01.236 --> 00:40:02.610
So everybody knows
how successful

00:40:02.610 --> 00:40:04.070
their games are in Japan.

00:40:04.070 --> 00:40:06.070
So we've hired
another developer.

00:40:06.070 --> 00:40:09.050
So they are working with them
for changing the monetization.

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:10.460
They're changing
their characters

00:40:10.460 --> 00:40:12.430
to give them a
different look and feel

00:40:12.430 --> 00:40:15.050
which appeals to the
Japanese audience.

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:15.850
The level design.

00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:16.810
Everything is changing.

00:40:16.810 --> 00:40:19.480
It's just the core engine,
the 3-D engine, is the same.

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:21.090
But everything
else, the gameplay,

00:40:21.090 --> 00:40:22.840
is changing to suit
the Japanese audience.

00:40:22.840 --> 00:40:24.881
DAN GALPIN: I think it's
been really interesting.

00:40:24.881 --> 00:40:26.120
We've seen both directions.

00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:28.940
We've seen companies
from Asia make strides

00:40:28.940 --> 00:40:31.050
into European and US markets.

00:40:31.050 --> 00:40:34.760
And it's always been, how do we
take something we know works,

00:40:34.760 --> 00:40:38.920
in terms of a general concept,
and bring that same concept

00:40:38.920 --> 00:40:41.880
to these markets in a way
that's palatable and exciting

00:40:41.880 --> 00:40:43.214
for them?

00:40:43.214 --> 00:40:44.755
And there have been
a couple of games

00:40:44.755 --> 00:40:46.421
that have really done
that successfully.

00:40:46.421 --> 00:40:50.690
But it's hard, there's
no question about it.

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:56.741
So in terms of game success.

00:40:56.741 --> 00:41:00.740
How do you define success
in terms of a game?

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:04.910
SOURABH AHUJA: So keeping
users in the game.

00:41:04.910 --> 00:41:07.030
So the retention.

00:41:07.030 --> 00:41:08.230
The money follows.

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:10.190
I mean, we can see even
from chat apps, right?

00:41:10.190 --> 00:41:13.480
If you keep users
in your app, you

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:15.000
will get eventually paid for it.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.440
So retention is the key.

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:20.830
There's so many apps
and games out there.

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:23.940
Users have short attention span.

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:26.612
Asian users have even
shorter attention span

00:41:26.612 --> 00:41:27.570
then the Western users.

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:30.210
So it's key to keep
them entertained.

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:31.710
Keep the updates coming.

00:41:31.710 --> 00:41:35.417
Plan out at least a year
in ahead of what content

00:41:35.417 --> 00:41:36.250
we're going to keep.

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:38.410
Because they eat
up content fast.

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:40.950
And then move on to the next
one if you don't give them

00:41:40.950 --> 00:41:44.860
something fast when they're
done with those three levels.

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:47.730
Make sure you have the fourth,
fifth, sixth, ready to go.

00:41:50.115 --> 00:41:51.740
ARI KARDASIS: Well,
of our three games,

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:54.220
they've sort of enjoyed
success in very different ways.

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:58.210
Say the same thing was
kind of a critical hit.

00:41:58.210 --> 00:42:02.170
The Disco Bees
monetized very well.

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:06.400
It's kind of a sturdy game
that is what you want.

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:11.120
And Make It Rain was kind of
a runaway, viral sensation.

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:13.050
So we don't know.

00:42:13.050 --> 00:42:16.530
In a nutshell, we
like the process

00:42:16.530 --> 00:42:18.920
of experimenting and finding
new ways to be successful.

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:20.570
And I think that
as we go forward,

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:23.960
we'll try to take
things from each game,

00:42:23.960 --> 00:42:27.350
combine them into
super games that

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:30.440
are successful in
two or three ways.

00:42:30.440 --> 00:42:34.089
Yeah, it's always
different for us.

00:42:34.089 --> 00:42:35.630
GUILHERME LACHAUT:
I think longevity,

00:42:35.630 --> 00:42:37.290
when it comes to gaming.

00:42:37.290 --> 00:42:39.800
We have games like "World at
Arms" or "Order &amp; Chaos Online"

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:41.722
that have been live for
more than two years.

00:42:41.722 --> 00:42:44.180
And we're still bringing new
content all the time to users.

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:47.210
And seeing those
users still being

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:48.950
focused on playing
the game every day.

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:50.960
The retention, the
engagement in those games

00:42:50.960 --> 00:42:54.420
that are celebrating their
two plus years, anniversaries,

00:42:54.420 --> 00:42:55.300
is very impressive.

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:57.360
And this is, I think,
what's the most interesting

00:42:57.360 --> 00:42:59.730
with the switch to
freemium is that now,

00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:05.007
not only games have
a very long life.

00:43:05.007 --> 00:43:07.340
I mean, you don't even know
now when you release a game.

00:43:07.340 --> 00:43:09.440
It could still be live in
five years with new content.

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:11.880
So that's really what was
the thrill with the industry,

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:14.550
is that everything
is changing so fast.

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:16.219
And there's always
new challenges.

00:43:16.219 --> 00:43:17.760
So for us, really
longevity and being

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:20.501
able to have our games
live after two plus years

00:43:20.501 --> 00:43:22.500
and then being able to
bring new content to them

00:43:22.500 --> 00:43:26.020
is really a sign of success.

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:26.980
KEITH PICHELMAN: Yeah.

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:29.410
We look at the same things,
especially early on in a game.

00:43:29.410 --> 00:43:31.215
We look for engagement
and longevity

00:43:31.215 --> 00:43:33.287
and make sure that it's
a fun game, that people

00:43:33.287 --> 00:43:34.370
are enjoying it, you know?

00:43:34.370 --> 00:43:37.235
We're looking at the reviews
and see how people react.

00:43:37.235 --> 00:43:41.110
And we do a lot of testing
and see, you know, people,

00:43:41.110 --> 00:43:42.720
do they want to play it again?

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:45.010
Did they not put
the device down?

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.249
Things like that.

00:43:47.249 --> 00:43:48.790
I would say, Concrete
Software, being

00:43:48.790 --> 00:43:52.370
that we're a smaller
company, 25 people,

00:43:52.370 --> 00:43:55.044
we are very careful
about our games.

00:43:55.044 --> 00:43:56.960
And we want to make sure
that they make money.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:44:00.390
And so we look closely
at the lifetime values.

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:03.240
We also look at how
much time and cost

00:44:03.240 --> 00:44:05.650
that goes into
the games as well.

00:44:05.650 --> 00:44:08.500
Like "PBA Bowling Challenge",
we spend a lot of time and money

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:11.580
keeping it up, creating new
events and things like that.

00:44:11.580 --> 00:44:14.740
Where we do have other games
that we call very successful,

00:44:14.740 --> 00:44:17.490
like our "Aces Spades"
and "Aces Gin Rummy" where

00:44:17.490 --> 00:44:19.780
we don't have to
spend a lot of time.

00:44:19.780 --> 00:44:21.700
It's actually ad based.

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:24.220
And we keep them updated.

00:44:24.220 --> 00:44:27.500
We keep them working
on the latest devices

00:44:27.500 --> 00:44:30.870
that we don't necessarily
spend a lot of time and efforts

00:44:30.870 --> 00:44:34.490
to create live events
or things like that.

00:44:34.490 --> 00:44:36.810
DAN GALPIN: I think in the
early version of Android,

00:44:36.810 --> 00:44:39.330
the most popular-- I don't
know how many of you were back

00:44:39.330 --> 00:44:40.890
in the early days of Android.

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:43.220
The most popular game
on Android market

00:44:43.220 --> 00:44:47.599
was actually a solitaire game.

00:44:47.599 --> 00:44:49.015
Because everyone
wanted solitaire,

00:44:49.015 --> 00:44:51.187
and it was about
50 kilobytes long.

00:44:51.187 --> 00:44:53.770
So it was a no brainer, everyone
just kept it on their device.

00:44:53.770 --> 00:44:55.770
I'm not sure how much
people actually played it,

00:44:55.770 --> 00:44:58.910
but it was on every
single person's phone.

00:44:58.910 --> 00:45:01.420
And there are
games that are just

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:04.250
going to be perennial
things, that people are going

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:06.870
to want to keep there, to have
that little experience all

00:45:06.870 --> 00:45:07.740
the time.

00:45:07.740 --> 00:45:09.420
Versus then there
are things that

00:45:09.420 --> 00:45:12.040
are more engaging and
require more depth.

00:45:12.040 --> 00:45:14.980
And that's a different
kind of success.

00:45:14.980 --> 00:45:16.625
LLOYD TULLUES: So
we look very heavily

00:45:16.625 --> 00:45:20.030
towards engagement and
retention metrics as well.

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:23.190
We love creating fantastic
content for our players.

00:45:23.190 --> 00:45:28.550
And so we will look closely in
terms of what they're consuming

00:45:28.550 --> 00:45:34.080
and what they come back
to, so we build upon that.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:36.370
So that's one of
the big ways that we

00:45:36.370 --> 00:45:37.750
measure the success
of our games.

00:45:37.750 --> 00:45:39.910
But one of the things that
I really like looking at

00:45:39.910 --> 00:45:45.250
is the peripheral emerging
behaviors of our users outside

00:45:45.250 --> 00:45:45.750
of the game.

00:45:45.750 --> 00:45:47.570
So when they start
creating content.

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:50.020
Like videos, or
they go on forums

00:45:50.020 --> 00:45:52.595
where they create
strategy guides, right?

00:45:52.595 --> 00:45:56.490
And they start sharing ideas
and approaches with one another.

00:45:56.490 --> 00:45:59.950
That's how we know, OK, we're
actually on to something here.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:02.630
And we can possibly
build on that.

00:46:02.630 --> 00:46:04.240
So that's always
very, very exciting.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:07.706
And then we've got other things,
but usually the rest follows.

00:46:07.706 --> 00:46:09.830
DAN GALPIN: I think one of
the most exciting things

00:46:09.830 --> 00:46:13.760
about mobile right
now is the ability

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:17.890
to directly interact with your
players and cycle really fast.

00:46:17.890 --> 00:46:20.280
I think for me, the coolest
thing about Google Play

00:46:20.280 --> 00:46:24.920
is you can come up with
an idea, make a change,

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:27.670
and have it out to
users within an hour.

00:46:27.670 --> 00:46:30.870
And that's crazy fast.

00:46:30.870 --> 00:46:35.690
You think about the console
era of just a few years ago.

00:46:35.690 --> 00:46:36.649
You'd finish your game.

00:46:36.649 --> 00:46:37.898
You'd send it off for testing.

00:46:37.898 --> 00:46:39.640
You would actually
get burnt into discs.

00:46:39.640 --> 00:46:41.681
A month or two months
later you would get it out.

00:46:41.681 --> 00:46:43.529
And then maybe you
could patch it later.

00:46:43.529 --> 00:46:45.570
And now we're in this
position where you can just

00:46:45.570 --> 00:46:47.220
continue to tweak and engage.

00:46:47.220 --> 00:46:49.370
And I think from a product
perspective, actually,

00:46:49.370 --> 00:46:52.225
for outside of Play
Games, it's actually

00:46:52.225 --> 00:46:54.550
Tag Manager is the one that
I'm super excited about,

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:56.990
to be able to actually analyze
trends and then tweak games

00:46:56.990 --> 00:46:59.150
very, very, very quickly
based upon those trends.

00:46:59.150 --> 00:47:01.160
I think it's super exciting.

